availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: This manuscript contains a number of calendars, with annotations, several medical treatises, and a tract on astrology, including the astrology of medicine. The manuscript concludes with some medical notes in later hands, in Scots, Latin, and Gaelic. Among these are the noted Beaton genealogies. The manuscript was produced in Ireland by Cairbre Ó Ceanmháin for John Beaton of Ballinabe in about 1563; John Beaton may have been present during the manuscript's production. Notes are added throughout the manuscript by several later members of the Beaton family.

summary.p: The transcription opens with a marginal note by a Beaton scribe and a poem on the alphabet. The astrological tract that concludes the manuscript contains an account of the movements of the sun, moon, planets, and constellations; the etymologies of their names; the parts of the body they govern; and the changes in the earth's seasons that coincide with changes in the heavens.

note.p: The tract quotes Albamasar (Abu Maʿshar) and Isidore [of Seville?], and possibly a treatise on the Astrolabe. No other versions of this Gaelic text are known at this time.

When fol. 105va begins, the text is discussing Libra, having apparently omitted details on the planetary conjunctions of Virgo. This seems likely to be a textual lacuna, as there is no sign of physical loss, judging by the (admittedly late) foliations and Libra immediately follows Virgo in the Zodiac, so it is not clear what an entire missing folio would have contained in order to span the gap.
